ani sovereignty referendum|1992]]\n| {{flag|Russia}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| Tatarstan reintegrated with Russia de facto in 1994, de jure in 2002\n|-\n| {{flag|Eritrea|1993}}\n| [[1993 Eritrean independence referendum|1993]]\n| {{flag|Ethiopia|1991}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|United States Virgin Islands}}\n| [[1993 United States Virgin Islands status referendum|1993]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| [[1993 Puerto Rican status referendum|1993]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Cura\u00e7ao}}\n| [[1993 Cura\u00e7ao status referendum|1993]]\n| {{flag|Kingdom of the Netherlands|name=Netherlands}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for restructuring the Netherlands Antilles\n|-\n| {{flag|Bonaire}}\n| [[1994 Bonaire status referendum|1994]]\n| {{flag|Kingdom of the Netherlands|name=Netherlands}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for keeping the status quo.\n|-\n| {{flag|Sint Maarten}}\n| [[1994 Sint Maarten status referendum|1994]]\n| {{flag|Kingdom of the Netherlands|name=Netherlands}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for keeping the status quo.\n|-\n| {{flag|Saba}}\n| [[1994 Saban status referendum|1994]]\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for keeping the status quo.\n|-\n| {{flag|Sint Eustatius}}\n| [[1994 Sint Eustatius status referendum|1994]]\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for keeping the status quo.\n|-\n| {{flag|Bermuda}}\n| [[1995 Bermudian independence referendum|1995]]\n| {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| \n|-\n| {{flag|Quebec}}\n| [[1995 Quebec referendum|1995]]\n| {{flag|Canada}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| \"No\" won by 1.16%.\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_Principality_of_Seborga_-v.svg}} [[Principality of Seborga|Seborga]]\n| [[Principality of Seborga#History|1995]]\n| {{flag|Italy}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| Residents voted 304 to 4 for independence.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Roth|first=Christopher F.|date=March 2015|title=Let's Split! A Complete Guide to Separatist Movements and Aspirant Nations, from Abkhazia to Zanzibar|publisher=Litwin Books, LLC|url=http://litwinbooks.com/LS-Italy.pdf|page=90|quote=In 1995, Giorgio held a referendum, with Seborgans opting for independence 304-4.}}</ref> Regarded by most to be a [[micronation]] rather than a ''de facto'' state.\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag_of_Anjouan.svg}} [[Anjouan#Secessionist/Autonomous Anjouan|Anjouan]]\n| [[1997 Anjouan independence referendum|1997]]\n| {{flag|Comoros}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|  {{Partial|[[List of states with limited recognition|''De facto'']]}}\n| {{No}}\n| Anjouan remained de facto independent until 2001\n|-\n| {{flag|Nevis}}\n| [[1998 Nevis independence referendum|1998]]\n| {{nowrap|{{flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| 62% of voters approved of independence, but a 2/3 majority was required.\n|-\n| {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| [[1998 Puerto Rican status referendum|1998]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|East Timor}}\n| [[1999 East Timorese independence referendum|1999]]\n| {{flag|Indonesia}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| The referendum was organised by the [[United Nations]]; independence was achieved in 2002\n|-\n| {{flag|Sint Maarten}}\n| [[2000 Sint Maarten status referendum|2000]]\n| {{flag|Kingdom of the Netherlands|name=Netherlands}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for becoming a country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands.\n|-\n| {{flag|Bonaire}}\n| [[2004 Bonaire status referendum|2004]]\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for integration with the Netherlands\n|-\n| {{flag|Saba}}\n| [[2004 Saban status referendum|2004]]\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for direct constitutional ties with the Netherlands\n|-\n| {{flag|Kurdistan}}\n| [[2005 Kurdistan Region independence referendum|2005]]\n| {{flag|Iraq|2004}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Cura\u00e7ao}}\n| [[2005 Cura\u00e7ao status referendum|2005]]\n| {{flag|Kingdom of the Netherlands|name=Netherlands}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted to become an Autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands\n|-\n| {{flag|Sint Eustatius}}\n| [[2005 Sint Eustatius status referendum|2005]]\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for remaining part of the Netherlands Antilles\n|-\n| {{flag|Montenegro}}\n| [[2006 Montenegrin independence referendum|2006]]\n| {{flag|Serbia and Montenegro}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|South Ossetia}}\n| [[2006 South Ossetian independence referendum|2006]]\n| {{flag|Georgia}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Partial|[[List of states with limited recognition|''De facto'']]}}\n| {{No}}\n| The issue was whether South Ossetia should retain its ''de facto'' independent status\n|-\n| {{flag|Transnistria|state}}\n| [[2006 Transnistrian independence referendum|2006]]\n| {{flag|Moldova}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Partial|[[List of states with limited recognition|''De facto'']]}}\n| {{No}}\n| The issue was whether Transnistria should retain its ''de facto'' independent status\n|-\n| {{flag|Tokelau|state}}\n| [[2006 Tokelauan self-determination referendum|2006]]\n| {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| {{Partial|Majority for associated status}}\n| {{No|Associated status not achieved}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| The referendum was on whether Tokelau should become an [[associated state]] of New Zealand.  This [[Political status of the Cook Islands and Niue|status]] is sometimes considered to be independence. 60% of voters approved, but a 2/3 majority was required.\n|-\n| {{flag|Tokelau|state}}\n| [[2007 Tokelauan self-determination referendum|2007]]\n| {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| {{Partial|Majority for associated status}}\n| {{No|Associated s