\n| {{No}}\n| The issue was whether the Luhnsk People's Republic should retain its ''de facto'' independent status. Only controls a portion of its claimed territory.<!-- Republic was declared on 27 April, referendum was on 11 May -->\n|-\n| {{flag|Veneto}}\n| [[2014 Venetian independence referendum|2014]]\n| {{flag|Italy}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| The referendum was conducted online and through self-organized voting booths by a private organization, [[Plebiscite 2013]], without voter verification, and without the cooperation of the Italian national or Venetian regional governments. 89% of residents voted to split from Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2586531/Venice-votes-split-Italy-89-citys-residents-opt-form-new-independent-state.html|title=Venice votes to split from Italy as 89% of the city's residents opt to form a new independent state|last=Roberts|first=Hannah|date=2014-03-21|website=Mail Online|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/venice-votes-independence-italy-585/|title=89% of Veneto residents vote for independence from Rome|last=|first=|date=2014-03-23|website=RT|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-10}}</ref> An official [[2017 Venetian autonomy referendum|referendum on Venetian autonomy]] took place on 22 October 2017, with 98% voting in favor of special autonomy for Veneto.\n|-\n| {{flag|Scotland}}\n| [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|2014]]\n| {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag_of_Catalonia.svg}} [[Catalonia]] <!-- Uses the independence flag since this column is for the proposed state -->\n| [[2014 Catalan self-determination referendum|2014]]\n| {{flag|Spain}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Sint Eustatius}}\n| [[2014 Sint Eustatius status referendum|2014]]\n| {{flag|Netherlands}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|A majority voted for autonomy within the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]], but low turnout invalidated the result.\n|-\n| [[File:Bandeira do movimento O Sul \u00c9 o Meu Pa\u00eds.svg|20px]] [[South Region, Brazil|South Brazil]]\n| [[The South is My Country#First edition|2016]]\n| {{flag|Brazil}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| Described as a \"Plebisul\", the turnout was only 2.91%.\n|-\n| {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| [[2017 Puerto Rican status referendum|2017]]\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| If a majority of voters selected the \"Independence/Free Association\" option, another independence referendum between those two options would've been held. However, a majority of voters voted for U.S. statehood.\n|-\n| {{flag|Kurdistan}}\n| [[2017 Kurdistan Region independence referendum|2017]]\n| {{flag|Iraq}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-41744376|title=Iraqi Kurds offer to 'freeze' independence referendum result|date=25 October 2017|accessdate=27 October 2017|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref>\n| {{No}} <!-- This is for recognition of the referendum, which was not recognized by Iraq, not potential recognition of a Kurdish state-->\n| The referendum also took place in the [[disputed territories of Northern Iraq]].\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag_of_Catalonia.svg}} [[Catalonia]]\n| [[2017 Catalan independence referendum|2017]]\n| {{flag|Spain}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-41785292 Catalonia independence: Spain takes charge of Catalan government] BBC News, 28 October 2017</ref>\n| {{No}}\n| The Parliament of Catalonia unilaterally declared the formation of a [[Catalan declaration of independence|Catalan Republic]] on 27 October 2017. The declaration was not recognized by the Government of Spain which continued to regard Catalonia as part of its sovereign territory and asserted direct control at the beginning of the workday on 30 October. On 31 October 2017 the Constitutional Court of Spain formally revoked the declaration with retroactive effect.<ref>http://www.huffingtonpost.es/2017/10/31/suspendida-la-declaracion-de-independencia-de-cataluna_a_23262184/</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Bandeira do movimento O Sul \u00c9 o Meu Pa\u00eds.svg|20px]] [[South Region, Brazil|South Brazil]]\n| [[The South is My Country#Second edition|2017]]\n| {{flag|Brazil}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n| Second edition of the referendum described as a \"Plebisul\", the turnout was only 1.72%.\n|-\n|{{flag|New Caledonia}}\n|[[2018 New Caledonian independence referendum|2018]]\n|{{flag|France}}\n|{{No}}\n|{{No}}\n|{{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Bougainville}}\n| [[2019 Bougainvillean independence referendum|2019]]\n| {{nowrap|{{flag|Papua New Guinea}}}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{tba|Subject to negotiation}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/11/bougainville-referendum-region-votes-overwhelmingly-for-independence-from-papua-new-guinea|title=Bougainville referendum: region votes overwhelmingly for independence from Papua New Guinea|last=Lyons|first=Kate|date=2019-12-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-11|language=en}} The referendum is nonbinding and the leadership of Papua New Guinea and Bougainville will negotiate, while the PNG parliament will have the final say.</ref>\n| {{Yes}}\n| Held between 23 November to 7 December 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-papua-bougainville-idUSKCN1UV0QK|title=Bougainville agrees with PNG to delay independence vote till November|last=Mair|first=John|date=2019-08-05|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-08-05|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/396000/bougainville-referendum-now-set-to-be-held-on-23-november|title=Bougainville referendum now set to be held on 23 November|date=2019-08-05|website=Radio New Zealand|language=en-nz|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> The vote was not binding and the Government of Papua New Guinea has the final say on what becomes of Bougainville as voters chose independence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/384471/bougainville-referendum-not-binding-pm|title=Bougainville referendum not binding - PM|date=2019-03-11|website=Radio New Zealand|language=en-nz|access-date=2019-03-18}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Scheduled independence referendums==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!Proposed State\n!Date\n!Current state\n!Recognition\n!Notes \n|-\n| {{flag|New Caledonia}}\n| [[2020 New Caledonian independence referendum|6 September 2020]]<ref>[https://guardian.ng/news/frances-new-caledonia-to-hold-independence-vote-in-2020/ France\u2019s New Caledonia to hold independence vote in 2020] The Guardian, 5 November 2019</ref>\n| {{flag|France}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Chuuk}}\n| [[2022 Chuukese independence referendum|March 2022]]<ref name=\"chuuk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pacific-micronesia/chuuk-independence-vote-postponed-as-china-u-s-pacific-contest-builds-idUSKCN20L09G?il=0|title=Chuuk independence vote postponed as China-U.S. Pacific contest builds|website=Reuters|date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| {{flag|Micronesia}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|Was scheduled for March 2020, but the Micronesian government announced that the vote had been postponed again.<ref name=\"chuuk\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Balkanization]]\n*[[Declaration of independence]]\n** [[Unilateral declaration of independence|Unilateral]]\n*[[Decolonization]]\n*[[Ethnic nationalism]]\n*[[Independence movement]]\n*[[Lists of active separatist movements]]\n*[[List of irredentist claims or disputes]]\n*[[List of proposed state mergers]]\n*[[List of sovereign states]]\n*[[List of territorial disputes]]\n*[[National liberation]]\n*[[Secession]]\n*[[Self-determination]]\n*[[Separatism]]\n*[[Sovereignty]]\n*[[Succession of states]]\n*[[Territorial integrity]]\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Independence referendums| ]]\n[[Category:Secession]]\n[[Category:Independence]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Referendum to decide whether a territory should become an independent country}}\n[[File:K-CNRT rally Dili 07'99-25.jpg|thumb|[[1999 East Timorese independence referendum|East Timorese independence referendum]] in 1999]]\n[[File:Southern Sudan Referendum1.jpg|thumb|[[2011 South Sudanese independence referendum|South Sudanese independence referendum]] in 2011]]\nAn '''independence referendum''' is a type of [[referendum]] in which the citizens of a [[territory]] decide whether the territory should become an [[Independence|independent]] [[sovereign state]]. An independence referendum that results in a vote for independence does not always ultimately result in independence.\n\nThe articles on specific referendums are linked with dates in the table on past referendums.\n\n==Procedure==\nAn independence referendum typically arises first after political success for [[nationalism|nationalists]] of a territory. This could come in the election of politicians or parties with [[separatism|separatist]] policies, or from pressure from [[list of nationalist organizations|nationalist organisations]].\n\n===Negotiations===\nNegotiations for the terms of an independence referendum may take place between the nationalists and the government which exercises sovereignty over the territory. If terms can be agreed, then the independence referendum can be held with its result binding, and respected by the [[international community]]. Independence referendums can be held without the consent of a national or the federal governments, then the international community will rely on several other factors, e.g. were the local people oppressed by the central government or not, to decide if the result can be recognized or not.\n\nVarious issues can be discussed in negotiations, such as the date and timing of the poll, as well as voter eligibility. For these instances, common electoral practice is often widely used, although there can be deviations, as seen with the lowering of the [[voting age]] for the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum]].\n\nOther issues to be negotiated include what question or questions should be on the ballot, and what the voting options could be. Independence referendums can offer options of greater [[autonomy]] as well as, or instead of, the status quo. They can also put forward other [[constitution]]al questions to ballot. The questions that referendums ask may be revised if parties involved in negotiations consider them to be too [[Leading question|leading]].\n\nNegotiations notably need to address what would make a result binding. For some independence referendums, a simple majority is required for one option. In other cases, a quota can be used, where a certain percentage of the vote or the electorate needs to be in favour of an option for it to be binding.\n\n[[File:2014-05-11. \u0420\u0435\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0443\u043c \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435 017.jpg|thumb|[[2014 Donbass status referendums|Donbass status referendum]] in 2014 was rejected as illegal by the [[First Yatsenyuk government|Ukrainian government]]]]\nSuccessful negotiations can be hard to achieve for nationalists, as governments can be reluctant to give up sovereignty. For example, nationalists planned to hold a referendum in [[Catalonia]] in 2014, but met opposition from the [[Spain|Spanish]] government. As a result, the [[2014 Catalan self-determination referendum|referendum that went ahead]] was unofficial and non-binding.\n\n===Aftermath===\nIn the event of a vote for independence, there may be negotiations on the terms of [[secession]] for the territory from the sovereign state. A [[declaration of independence]] for a new state is then made, and international recognition can follow, as well as membership of international organisations such as the [[United Nations]]. In cases involving non-binding referendums, this can lead to a [[unilateral declaration of independence]], and therefore [[List of states with limited recognition|partially recognised]] or [[self-proclaimed]] states.\n\nIn the event of a vote against independence, there may still be a strong nationalist movement and calls for there to be a rerun of the independence referendum. For example, after two referendums in [[Quebec]], the [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] has continued to raise the prospect of holding another referendum,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-29077213|title=Neverendum referendum: Voting on independence, Quebec-style|date=8 September 2014|work=[[BBC News Online]]|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> and the [[Scottish National Party]] has said that there should be a repeat of the 2014 referendum if the [[United Kingdom]] leaves the [[European Union]].\n{{clear}}\n\n== Past independence referendums ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n!Proposed State\n!Year\n!Former State\n!Majority for Independence\n!Independence\n!Recognition\n!Notes\n|-\n| {{flag|Chile}}\n| [[1817 Chilean independence referendum|1817]]\n| {{flagicon image|Flag_of_Cross_of_Burgundy.svg}} [[Captaincy General of Chile]] \n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{No}}\n| Chile would [[Chilean Declaration of Independence|declare independence]] in 1818 and would secure independence following the [[Chilean War of Independence]].\n|-\n| {{flag|Liberia}}\n| [[1846 Liberian independence referendum|1846]]\n| [[American Colonization Society]]\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of the Republic of Maryland.svg}} [[Republic of Maryland|Maryland]]\n| [[1853 Maryland independence referendum|1853]]\n| [[Maryland State Colonization Society]]\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| {{flag|Norway}}\n| [[1905 Norwegian union dissolution referendum|1905]]\n| {{nowrap|{{flagicon image|Union Jack of Sweden and Norway (1844-1905).svg}} [[Union between Sweden and Norway|Sweden\u2013Norway]]}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| The referendum was on whether voters approved the ratified di